A '''decagonal number''' is a [[figurate number]] that extends the concept of [[triangular number|triangular]] and [[square number]]s to the [[decagon]] (a ten-sided polygon). However, unlike the triangular and square numbers, the patterns involved in the construction of decagonal numbers are not rotationally symmetrical. Specifically, the  ''n''th decagonal numbers counts the number of dots in a pattern of ''n'' nested decagons, all sharing a common corner, where the ''i''th decagon in the pattern has sides made of ''i'' dots spaced one unit apart from each other. The ''n''-th decagonal number is given by the formula
: <math>D_n = 4n^2 - 3n.</math>
The first few decagonal numbers are:
: [[0 (number)|0]], [[1 (number)|1]], [[10 (number)|10]], [[27 (number)|27]], [[52 (number)|52]], [[85 (number)|85]], [[126 (number)|126]], [[175 (number)|175]], 232, 297, 370, 451, 540, 637, 742, 855, 976, 1105, 1242, 1387, 1540, 1701, 1870, 2047, 2232, 2425, 2626, 2835, 3052, 3277, 3510, 3751, [[4000 (number)|4000]], 4257, 4522, 4795, 5076, 5365, 5662, 5967, 6280, 6601, 6930, 7267, 7612, 7965, 8326 {{OEIS|id=A001107}}

The ''n''-th decagonal number can also be calculated by adding the square of ''n'' to thrice the (''n''—1)-th [[pronic number]] or, to put it algebraically, as 
: <math>D_n = n^2 + 3(n^2 - n).</math>

== Properties ==

* Decagonal numbers consistently alternate [[Even and odd numbers#Parity in mathematics|parity]].

